{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475135"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:29:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:29:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12533"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12533"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.04,0.86,0.07,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5032"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92902"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5032"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12533"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76254"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1899"},{"type":"tags","id":"3418"},{"type":"tags","id":"4836"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31872"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43890"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92902"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parents with a several month history of passing hard and painful stools, along with faecal incontinence. The parents report that this had started soon after toilet training him. The child has also grown more irritable and has decreased appetite. There has not been vomiting, fever or weight loss. He has no significant medical history, has achieved all his developmental milestones, and his immunisations are up to date. On examination, he appears well with a distended abdomen. A palpable faecal mass is noted in the left lower quadrant and an anal fissure is also seen. Neurological examination of the lower limbs is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Irritable bowel syndrome","Inflammatory bowel disease","Functional constipation","Hirschsprung\u0027s disease","Coeliac disease"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms and examination findings described in this question are consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Efunctional constipation\u003C/strong\u003E in a young child, with encopresis as a presentation. The child has a history of passing hard and painful stools, faecal incontinence and a distended abdomen with palpable faecal masses. An anal fissure is a common complication of functional constipation, due to the passage of hard stools.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnostic criteria for functional constipation are as below and must include \u22652 criteria for at least one month in infants or two months in older children:\u003Cbr /\u003E- \u22642 stools/week\u003Cbr /\u003E- History of retentive posturing or excessive volitional stool retention (ie withholding or incomplete evacuation)\u003Cbr /\u003E- History of painful or hard bowel movements\u003Cbr /\u003E- History of large-diameter stools\u003Cbr /\u003E- Presence of a large faecal mass in the rectum\u003Cbr /\u003EIn toilet-trained children, the following additional criteria may be used:\u003Cbr /\u003E- At least one episode per week of soiling/incontinence after the acquisition of toileting skills\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial investigation in a patient with suspected functional constipation would be a rectal examination which may reveal impacted faeces or other abnormalities. However, in children a digital rectal examination could be quite traumatic and it would be more appropriate to start treatment without taking the examination any further than a visual inspection of the anus and perineum. Another reason for not considering a digital rectal examination is the presence of an anal fissure, which would make such an attempted procedure extremely painful and unlikely to produce any useful information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment typically involves a combination of dietary changes including increasing fibre and fluid intake and behavioural modification such as encouraging regular toilet habits and sitting on the toilet at the same time every day. Osmotic and lubricant laxatives may also be used depending on the severity of constipation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIrritable bowel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Einflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E are less likely as they typically present with other features such as diarrhoea, bloody stools, and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHirschsprung\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E is a congenital disorder that can cause chronic constipation but it usually presents in infancy with failure to pass meconium and other symptoms such as abdominal swelling, tenderness, vomiting and failure to thrive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoeliac disease\u003C/strong\u003E and functional constipation can present with abdominal pain, bloating, and changes in bowel habits. However, in coeliac disease, other symptoms such as diarrhoea, weight loss, and fatigue may also be present. In functional constipation, the primary symptom is difficulty in passing stools. A blood test to check for anti-TTG (Tissue tranglutaminase) antibodies is usually performed to diagnose coeliac disease. However, in functional constipation, there are no specific laboratory tests to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Functional constipation is a common presentation in young children.","Treatment includes dietary changes, behavioral modification and laxative use"],"references":["Benninga MA, Faure C, Hyman PE, et al. Childhood Functional Gastrointestinal Disorders: Neonate/Toddler. Gastroenterology 2016.","National Institute for Health and Care and Excellence (2017) Constipation in children and young People: diagnosis and management (NICE Guideline 99). Available at https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/CG99","Tabbers MM, DiLorenzo C, Berger MY, et al. Evaluation and treatment of functional constipation in infants and children: evidence-based recommendations from ESPGHAN and NASPGHAN. J Pediatr Gastroenterol Nutr 2014; 58:258."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76254"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12533"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76254"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-19T20:17:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-19T20:18:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5032"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92902"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemC